// ============================================================
// INSTANCE DB for Function Block
// ============================================================
// An Instance DB stores the static (VAR) data for one specific
// call of a Function Block. You need ONE Instance DB per call.
//
// Example: If FB "T2O_CompressorControl" is called once → 1 Instance DB
//          If same FB called for 3 separate compressor banks → 3 Instance DBs
//
// The Instance DB structure is INHERITED from the FB's VAR section.
// You do not define the structure here — only override initial values.
// ============================================================

DATA_BLOCK "[FBName]_[EquipmentTag]_DB"
TITLE =Instance DB — [FBName] — [Equipment description]
//
// References FB: "[FBName]"
// Equipment: [Equipment tag and description]
//
VERSION : 0.1
"[FBName]"           // This line makes it an Instance DB for the named FB

BEGIN
// ---- Optional: override initial values from FB defaults ----
// Only include lines where you want non-zero starting values.
// Syntax: StructName.MemberName := value;

  SCADA.Setpoint1 := [value];    // e.g. high level setpoint
  SCADA.Setpoint2 := [value];    // e.g. low level setpoint

// All other values default to 0 / FALSE
END_DATA_BLOCK


// ============================================================
// HOW TO CREATE THIS INSTANCE DB IN SIMATIC MANAGER
// (if not compiling from AWL source)
// ============================================================
//
// Method A — Compile from AWL source (recommended):
//   1. Include this file in your AWL source
//   2. Import and compile in SIMATIC Manager
//   3. Instance DB appears in Blocks folder
//
// Method B — Manual creation in SIMATIC Manager:
//   1. In SIMATIC Manager, open your project
//   2. Navigate to the Blocks folder
//   3. Menu: Insert → S7 Block → Data Block  (or right-click → Insert New Object → Data Block)
//   4. Enter the DB number in the Properties dialog → OK
//   5. In the "New Data Block" dialog that opens:
//      → Select "Data block referencing a function block"
//      → In the dropdown, select "[FBName]"
//   6. Click OK
//   7. The Instance DB is created with the FB's full VAR structure
//   8. Optional: Open DB (double-click) → switch to Data View to set initial values
//
// ============================================================
// CALLING THE FB WITH THIS INSTANCE DB
// ============================================================
//
// In OB1 or calling FB:
//
// NETWORK
// TITLE =Call [FBName] for [equipment]
//
//       CALL  "[FBName]", "[FBName]_[EquipmentTag]_DB" (
//            // Input parameters (VAR_INPUT) if declared:
//            // InputParam  := source_value,
//            // Output parameters (VAR_OUTPUT) if declared:
//            // OutputParam := destination
//            );
//
//       NOP   0;
//
// OR with absolute addressing (no Symbol Table needed):
//
//       CALL  FB [n], DB [m]
//
// ============================================================
// IMPORTANT AFTER MODIFYING THE FB
// ============================================================
//
// If you change the FB's VAR section (add/remove/rename variables):
//   1. Recompile the FB source
//   2. The Instance DB structure is now STALE
//   3. Regenerate the Instance DB:
//      - Method: Delete old DB, recreate using Method B above
//      - OR: Right-click DB → Object Properties → Update DB
//   4. Re-enter any initial values that were set
//
// A mismatched Instance DB causes WRONG data at wrong offsets — silent errors!
//
// ============================================================
